\section*{The Rules}
One Game Master (GM) leads the game, with up to six players recommended. The game is played using six-sided dice (D6). Any challenging action requires judgement by the dice-lords. To resolve a challenge:

\begin{enumerate}
   \item Roll one D6 for pure luck. Roll one additional D6 if you character has relevant knowledge, judged by the Game Master. Roll yet one additional D6 if the player in detail can explain and or perform the action they are trying to achieve.
   \item Choose the highest roll, where 1 signifies total failure and 6 represents complete success, with everything else falling somewhere in between.
   \item The GM narrates the outcome based on the roll.
\end{enumerate}

\section*{The Acts}
A play is divided into five acts: The "Introduction" sets up the story and conflict, the "Rising Action" builds tension, the "Climax" delivers the turning point, the "Falling Action" deals with the aftermath, and the "Conclusion" resolves the plot and reveals the protagonist's fate, with little to no pause as one act flows seamlessly into the next.

Poor performance on stage only makes the already rowdy crowd even more unruly.

\section*{The Audience}
Ah, the theater—a stage is nothing without its audience, ever eager to banter and challenge the performers.

The mood of the audience is tracked on a sliding scale from -5 to +5. Each success or failure on stage shifts the needle one way or the other. But beware, a delighted crowd can be just as unpredictable as an angry one.

\section*{Final Bow}

The game ends when the final scene is played and the audience’s mood is set. The Game Master decides your fate—applause or boos.

